Washington Street, west side, north from Perry Street. September 24, 1930.

P. L. Sperr.

156, 158 Perry Street, south side, west of Washington Street. No. 158 is the one-story frame structure. 1932.

J. Clarence Davies Collection, Museum of the City of New York. Negative No. 106.

Washington Street, west side, from Perry Street to West 10th (formerly Amos) Street. The Beadleston & Woerz Brewery runs through the block from the south side of Charles Street to the north side of West 10th Street. In the foreground, Charles Lane (formerly Pig Alley) runs through the block, halfway between Perry and Charles Streets, from Washington to West Streets.
This land on the west side of Washington Street, between Perry and Christopher Streets, was the site of the State Prison during the first quarter of the nineteenth century.

July 30, 1932.

P. L. Sperr.

Washington Street, east side, north from and including Perry Street, showing also the cleared west side from Charles Lane to 11th Street. January 18, 1932.

P. L. Sperr.

143 and 141 Perry Street, north side, east of Washington Street (left, clearance at the N.E. corner). On the right, No. 139 formerly stood.

August 3, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

Perry Street, north side, east from Washington Street, showing at the N.E. corner a clearance that will be improved by a 1-story garage. On Greenwich Street appears the Ninth Ave. Elevated Line.

August 3, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

Washington Street, east side, north from Perry (right) to West 11th Streets, showing a demolition at the N.E. corner of Perry Street that will provide a site for a 1-story garage. The four story houses adjoining the clearance on the left will be included in this project. Appearing on the right are Nos. 143 and 141 Perry Street. They will remain.

August 3, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.
